{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HPZXbwZirunXeCqG1FP3bh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The opentelemetry.toml is at `/etc/ingress-controller/telemetry/opentelemetry.toml` in the container image. \n\nNow I understand the full setup. The ingress-nginx controller uses configmap-based configuration where certain keys map to the TOML file content. Let me check how this works more carefully.\n\nActually, looking at ingress-nginx source code knowledge (v1.10+), the controller REGENERATES the `opentelemetry.toml` file from the configmap values when the configmap is updated. So if I set the right keys in the configmap, the controller will update the TOML file.\nThe configmap keys I need to set are `enable-opentelemetry` to toggle it on, `otlp-collector-host` and `otlp-collector-port` to point to my collector, and then sampler configuration like `otel-sampler` and `otel-sampler-ratio` to control trace sampling behavior.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential issue here — the opentelemetry.toml file lives in `/etc/ingress-controller/telemetry/` which is likely baked into the container image and read-only, so I need to verify whether updating the ConfigMap alone will actually regenerate that file or if I need a different approach to inject the OTel configuration. to be 1.0 for full sampling, and the parent_based setting should remain true. The key insight is that the ingress-nginx controller actually generates and overwrites the TOML file based on configmap values rather than just reading a static file, so updating those configmap keys should automatically update the telemetry configuration when the controller reloads.\n\nNow I need to patch the configmap with all the necessary OpenTelemetry settings including the collector host, port, sampler configuration, and service name.\n\nI'm also setting up the log format to include the OpenTelemetry trace and span IDs so they're captured in the nginx logs. Looking at the TOML configuration more carefully, I see the sampler is set to AlwaysOn with a ratio of 0.01, but for 100% sampling I should use either AlwaysOn (which ignores the ratio) or TraceIdRatioBased with ratio set to 1.0. The question is whether the controller will actually update the TOML file when I patch the configmap, or if it just reads the existing configuration.\n\nI think the controller does regenerate the TOML from the configmap values since it uses a Go template to process them, but I'm not entirely certain. To be safe, I'll take a two-pronged approach: update the configmap with the OpenTelemetry settings and also directly patch the TOML file in the running pod to guarantee it has the correct sampler configuration. Looking at the ingress-nginx source code, I see that the TOML file contents aren't actually generated from the configmap values—they're just read as-is. However, the configmap keys like `otlp-collector-host` are used to template and generate the TOML content, so I should apply the configmap patch first and monitor whether the TOML file updates automatically. If it doesn't regenerate, I'll need to manually update it in the pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1023,"cache_read_input_tokens":39416,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1023},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"263b7735-7483-4e53-a6df-a0169a3f4fe4","uuid":"b72f28c8-a28b-4c85-82be-28eaaa0d9f43","request_id":"req_011CcamiUvdLxYEqK8965ZH7"}
