{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LCsTurNBo1WA2xvfKM9D1C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see from the strings output that the binary has a reference to `EnableOpentelemetry` as a field name. Also I can see the template for the TOML file:\n```\nexporter = \"otlp\"\n[exporters.otlp]\n```\n\nThis confirms the TOML format. Now I need to understand how the controller maps configmap keys to the TOML content.\n\nBased on my knowledge of ingress-nginx source code, the `Configuration` struct has these fields:\n- `EnableOpentelemetry bool`\n- `OpentelemetryConfig string` (path to TOML file)\n- `OtlpCollectorHost string`\n- `OtlpCollectorPort int`\n- `OtelSampler string`\n- `OtelSamplerRatio float64`\n- `OtelSamplerParentBased bool`\n- `OtelServiceName string`\n- `OtelMaxExportBatchSize int`\n- `OtelScheduleDelayMillis int`\n- `OtelMaxQueueSize int`\n\nThe controller generates the TOML file from these values when `EnableOpentelemetry` is true, mapping configmap keys in kebab-case to the corresponding struct fields. Finishing the field mappings for the remaining OTel configuration options, then I need to apply a configmap patch to the ingress-nginx-controller with all these OTel settings plus the log-format-upstream requirement. The nginx variables `$opentelemetry_trace_id` and `$opentelemetry_span_id` are provided by the otel_ng module, which I'll need to verify is properly configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11437,"cache_read_input_tokens":40439,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11437},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"263b7735-7483-4e53-a6df-a0169a3f4fe4","uuid":"9c50445a-5dfc-4043-af37-05238cb9df48","request_id":"req_011CcammKxCxp8b6LTq831Tk"}
